5248 
5249 /**
5250  * Retrieve the number of fix-its for the given completion index.
5251  *
5252  * Calling this makes sense only if CXCodeComplete_IncludeCompletionsWithFixIts
5253  * option was set.
5254  *
5255  * \param results The structure keeping all completion results
5256  *
5257  * \param completion_index The index of the completion
5258  *
5259  * \return The number of fix-its which must be applied before the completion at
5260  * completion_index can be applied
5261  */
5262 CINDEX_LINKAGE unsigned
5263 clang_getCompletionNumFixIts(CXCodeCompleteResults *results,
5264  unsigned completion_index);
5265 
5266 /**
5267  * Fix-its that *must* be applied before inserting the text for the
5268  * corresponding completion.
5269  *
5270  * By default, clang_codeCompleteAt() only returns completions with empty
5271  * fix-its. Extra completions with non-empty fix-its should be explicitly
5272  * requested by setting CXCodeComplete_IncludeCompletionsWithFixIts.
5273  *
5274  * For the clients to be able to compute position of the cursor after applying
5275  * fix-its, the following conditions are guaranteed to hold for
5276  * replacement_range of the stored fix-its:
5277  * - Ranges in the fix-its are guaranteed to never contain the completion
5278  * point (or identifier under completion point, if any) inside them, except
5279  * at the start or at the end of the range.
5280  * - If a fix-it range starts or ends with completion point (or starts or
5281  * ends after the identifier under completion point), it will contain at
5282  * least one character. It allows to unambiguously recompute completion
5283  * point after applying the fix-it.
5284  *
5285  * The intuition is that provided fix-its change code around the identifier we
5286  * complete, but are not allowed to touch the identifier itself or the
5287  * completion point. One example of completions with corrections are the ones
5288  * replacing '.' with '->' and vice versa:
5289  *
5290  * std::unique_ptr<std::vector<int>> vec_ptr;
5291  * In 'vec_ptr.^', one of the completions is 'push_back', it requires
5292  * replacing '.' with '->'.
5293  * In 'vec_ptr->^', one of the completions is 'release', it requires
5294  * replacing '->' with '.'.
5295  *
5296  * \param results The structure keeping all completion results
5297  *
5298  * \param completion_index The index of the completion
5299  *
5300  * \param fixit_index The index of the fix-it for the completion at
5301  * completion_index
5302  *
5303  * \param replacement_range The fix-it range that must be replaced before the
5304  * completion at completion_index can be applied
5305  *
5306  * \returns The fix-it string that must replace the code at replacement_range
5307  * before the completion at completion_index can be applied
5308  */
5309 CINDEX_LINKAGE CXString clang_getCompletionFixIt(
5310  CXCodeCompleteResults *results, unsigned completion_index,
5311  unsigned fixit_index, CXSourceRange *replacement_range);
5312 
5313 /**
5314  * Flags that can be passed to \c clang_codeCompleteAt() to
5315  * modify its behavior.
5316  *
5317  * The enumerators in this enumeration can be bitwise-OR'd together to
5318  * provide multiple options to \c clang_codeCompleteAt().
5319  */
5320 enum CXCodeComplete_Flags {
5321  /**
5322  * Whether to include macros within the set of code
5323  * completions returned.
5324  */
5325  CXCodeComplete_IncludeMacros = 0x01,
5326 
5327  /**
5328  * Whether to include code patterns for language constructs
5329  * within the set of code completions, e.g., for loops.
5330  */
5331  CXCodeComplete_IncludeCodePatterns = 0x02,
5332 
5333  /**
5334  * Whether to include brief documentation within the set of code
5335  * completions returned.
5336  */
5337  CXCodeComplete_IncludeBriefComments = 0x04,
5338 
5339  /**
5340  * Whether to speed up completion by omitting top- or namespace-level entities
5341  * defined in the preamble. There's no guarantee any particular entity is
5342  * omitted. This may be useful if the headers are indexed externally.
5343  */
5344  CXCodeComplete_SkipPreamble = 0x08,
5345 
5346  /**
5347  * Whether to include completions with small
5348  * fix-its, e.g. change '.' to '->' on member access, etc.
5349  */
5350  CXCodeComplete_IncludeCompletionsWithFixIts = 0x10
5351 };
5352 
5353 /**
5354  * Bits that represent the context under which completion is occurring.
5355  *
5356  * The enumerators in this enumeration may be bitwise-OR'd together if multiple
5357  * contexts are occurring simultaneously.
5358  */
5359 enum CXCompletionContext {
5360  /**
5361  * The context for completions is unexposed, as only Clang results
5362  * should be included. (This is equivalent to having no context bits set.)
5363  */
5364  CXCompletionContext_Unexposed = 0,
5365 
5366  /**
5367  * Completions for any possible type should be included in the results.
5368  */
5369  CXCompletionContext_AnyType = 1 << 0,
5370 
5371  /**
5372  * Completions for any possible value (variables, function calls, etc.)
5373  * should be included in the results.
5374  */
5375  CXCompletionContext_AnyValue = 1 << 1,
5376  /**
5377  * Completions for values that resolve to an Objective-C object should
5378  * be included in the results.
5379  */
5380  CXCompletionContext_ObjCObjectValue = 1 << 2,
5381  /**
5382  * Completions for values that resolve to an Objective-C selector
5383  * should be included in the results.
5384  */
5385  CXCompletionContext_ObjCSelectorValue = 1 << 3,
5386  /**
5387  * Completions for values that resolve to a C++ class type should be
5388  * included in the results.
5389  */
5390  CXCompletionContext_CXXClassTypeValue = 1 << 4,
5391 
5392  /**
5393  * Completions for fields of the member being accessed using the dot
5394  * operator should be included in the results.
5395  */
5396  CXCompletionContext_DotMemberAccess = 1 << 5,
5397  /**
5398  * Completions for fields of the member being accessed using the arrow
5399  * operator should be included in the results.
5400  */
5401  CXCompletionContext_ArrowMemberAccess = 1 << 6,
5402  /**
5403  * Completions for properties of the Objective-C object being accessed
5404  * using the dot operator should be included in the results.
5405  */
5406  CXCompletionContext_ObjCPropertyAccess = 1 << 7,
5407 
5408  /**
5409  * Completions for enum tags should be included in the results.
5410  */
5411  CXCompletionContext_EnumTag = 1 << 8,
5412  /**
5413  * Completions for union tags should be included in the results.
5414  */
5415  CXCompletionContext_UnionTag = 1 << 9,
5416  /**
5417  * Completions for struct tags should be included in the results.
5418  */
5419  CXCompletionContext_StructTag = 1 << 10,
5420 
5421  /**
5422  * Completions for C++ class names should be included in the results.
5423  */
5424  CXCompletionContext_ClassTag = 1 << 11,
5425  /**
5426  * Completions for C++ namespaces and namespace aliases should be
5427  * included in the results.
5428  */
5429  CXCompletionContext_Namespace = 1 << 12,
5430  /**
5431  * Completions for C++ nested name specifiers should be included in
5432  * the results.
5433  */
5434  CXCompletionContext_NestedNameSpecifier = 1 << 13,
5435 
5436  /**
5437  * Completions for Objective-C interfaces (classes) should be included
5438  * in the results.
5439  */
5440  CXCompletionContext_ObjCInterface = 1 << 14,
5441  /**
5442  * Completions for Objective-C protocols should be included in
5443  * the results.
5444  */
5445  CXCompletionContext_ObjCProtocol = 1 << 15,
5446  /**
5447  * Completions for Objective-C categories should be included in
5448  * the results.
5449  */
5450  CXCompletionContext_ObjCCategory = 1 << 16,
5451  /**
5452  * Completions for Objective-C instance messages should be included
5453  * in the results.
5454  */
5455  CXCompletionContext_ObjCInstanceMessage = 1 << 17,
5456  /**
5457  * Completions for Objective-C class messages should be included in
5458  * the results.
5459  */
5460  CXCompletionContext_ObjCClassMessage = 1 << 18,
5461  /**
5462  * Completions for Objective-C selector names should be included in
5463  * the results.
5464  */
5465  CXCompletionContext_ObjCSelectorName = 1 << 19,
5466 
5467  /**
5468  * Completions for preprocessor macro names should be included in
5469  * the results.
5470  */
5471  CXCompletionContext_MacroName = 1 << 20,
5472 
5473  /**
5474  * Natural language completions should be included in the results.
5475  */
5476  CXCompletionContext_NaturalLanguage = 1 << 21,
5477 
5478  /**
5479  * #include file completions should be included in the results.
5480  */
5481  CXCompletionContext_IncludedFile = 1 << 22,
5482 
5483  /**
5484  * The current context is unknown, so set all contexts.
5485  */
5486  CXCompletionContext_Unknown = ((1 << 23) - 1)
5487 };

5489 /**
5490  * Returns a default set of code-completion options that can be
5491  * passed to\c clang_codeCompleteAt().
5492  */
5493 CINDEX_LINKAGE unsigned clang_defaultCodeCompleteOptions(void);
5494 
5495 /**
5496  * Perform code completion at a given location in a translation unit.
5497  *
5498  * This function performs code completion at a particular file, line, and
5499  * column within source code, providing results that suggest potential
5500  * code snippets based on the context of the completion. The basic model
5501  * for code completion is that Clang will parse a complete source file,
5502  * performing syntax checking up to the location where code-completion has
5503  * been requested. At that point, a special code-completion token is passed
5504  * to the parser, which recognizes this token and determines, based on the
5505  * current location in the C/Objective-C/C++ grammar and the state of
5506  * semantic analysis, what completions to provide. These completions are
5507  * returned via a new \c CXCodeCompleteResults structure.
5508  *
5509  * Code completion itself is meant to be triggered by the client when the
5510  * user types punctuation characters or whitespace, at which point the
5511  * code-completion location will coincide with the cursor. For example, if \c p
5512  * is a pointer, code-completion might be triggered after the "-" and then
5513  * after the ">" in \c p->. When the code-completion location is after the ">",
5514  * the completion results will provide, e.g., the members of the struct that
5515  * "p" points to. The client is responsible for placing the cursor at the
5516  * beginning of the token currently being typed, then filtering the results
5517  * based on the contents of the token. For example, when code-completing for
5518  * the expression \c p->get, the client should provide the location just after
5519  * the ">" (e.g., pointing at the "g") to this code-completion hook. Then, the
5520  * client can filter the results based on the current token text ("get"), only
5521  * showing those results that start with "get". The intent of this interface
5522  * is to separate the relatively high-latency acquisition of code-completion
5523  * results from the filtering of results on a per-character basis, which must
5524  * have a lower latency.
5525  *
5526  * \param TU The translation unit in which code-completion should
5527  * occur. The source files for this translation unit need not be
5528  * completely up-to-date (and the contents of those source files may
5529  * be overridden via \p unsaved_files). Cursors referring into the
5530  * translation unit may be invalidated by this invocation.
5531  *
5532  * \param complete_filename The name of the source file where code
5533  * completion should be performed. This filename may be any file
5534  * included in the translation unit.
5535  *
5536  * \param complete_line The line at which code-completion should occur.
5537  *
5538  * \param complete_column The column at which code-completion should occur.
5539  * Note that the column should point just after the syntactic construct that
5540  * initiated code completion, and not in the middle of a lexical token.
5541  *
5542  * \param unsaved_files the Files that have not yet been saved to disk
5543  * but may be required for parsing or code completion, including the
5544  * contents of those files. The contents and name of these files (as
5545  * specified by CXUnsavedFile) are copied when necessary, so the
5546  * client only needs to guarantee their validity until the call to
5547  * this function returns.
5548  *
5549  * \param num_unsaved_files The number of unsaved file entries in \p
5550  * unsaved_files.
5551  *
5552  * \param options Extra options that control the behavior of code
5553  * completion, expressed as a bitwise OR of the enumerators of the
5554  * CXCodeComplete_Flags enumeration. The
5555  * \c clang_defaultCodeCompleteOptions() function returns a default set
5556  * of code-completion options.
5557  *
5558  * \returns If successful, a new \c CXCodeCompleteResults structure
5559  * containing code-completion results, which should eventually be
5560  * freed with \c clang_disposeCodeCompleteResults(). If code
5561  * completion fails, returns NULL.
5562  */
5563 CINDEX_LINKAGE
5564 CXCodeCompleteResults *
5565 clang_codeCompleteAt(CXTranslationUnit TU, const char *complete_filename,
5566  unsigned complete_line, unsigned complete_column,
5567  struct CXUnsavedFile *unsaved_files,
5568  unsigned num_unsaved_files, unsigned options);
5569 
5570 /**
5571  * Sort the code-completion results in case-insensitive alphabetical
5572  * order.
5573  *
5574  * \param Results The set of results to sort.
5575  * \param NumResults The number of results in \p Results.
5576  */
5577 CINDEX_LINKAGE
5578 void clang_sortCodeCompletionResults(CXCompletionResult *Results,
5579  unsigned NumResults);
5580 
5581 /**

6423 /**
6424  * Index the given source file and the translation unit corresponding
6425  * to that file via callbacks implemented through #IndexerCallbacks.
6426  *
6427  * \param client_data pointer data supplied by the client, which will
6428  * be passed to the invoked callbacks.
6429  *
6430  * \param index_callbacks Pointer to indexing callbacks that the client
6431  * implements.
6432  *
6433  * \param index_callbacks_size Size of #IndexerCallbacks structure that gets
6434  * passed in index_callbacks.
6435  *
6436  * \param index_options A bitmask of options that affects how indexing is
6437  * performed. This should be a bitwise OR of the CXIndexOpt_XXX flags.
6438  *
6439  * \param[out] out_TU pointer to store a \c CXTranslationUnit that can be
6440  * reused after indexing is finished. Set to \c NULL if you do not require it.
6441  *
6442  * \returns 0 on success or if there were errors from which the compiler could
6443  * recover. If there is a failure from which there is no recovery, returns
6444  * a non-zero \c CXErrorCode.
6445  *
6446  * The rest of the parameters are the same as #clang_parseTranslationUnit.
6447  */
6448 CINDEX_LINKAGE int clang_indexSourceFile(
6449  CXIndexAction, CXClientData client_data, IndexerCallbacks *index_callbacks,
6450  unsigned index_callbacks_size, unsigned index_options,
6451  const char *source_filename, const char *const *command_line_args,
6452  int num_command_line_args, struct CXUnsavedFile *unsaved_files,
6453  unsigned num_unsaved_files, CXTranslationUnit *out_TU, unsigned TU_options);
6454
